    "centre": {
        "title": "The Centre",
        "difficulty": 0,
        "description": [
            "The centre of the board is the region in which pieces are typically at their ",
            {
                "type": "glossary_button",
                "text": "most effective",
                "value": "material_value",
                "punctuation": ","
            },
            " granting the highest mobility and ",
            {
                "type": "glossary_button",
                "text": "coverage",
                "value": "piece_vision"
            },
            " by limiting the maximum distance to any other part of the board.",
            "\nA bishop placed in the centre can see to all four corners, and a knight will not have its movement",
            " blocked by the edges of the board.",
            "\n\nThis makes the centre a ",
            {
                "type": "glossary_button",
                "text": "positional",
                "value": "positional_chess"
            },
            " stronghold, and much of opening theory is dedicated to fighting for ",
            {
                "type": "glossary_button",
                "text": "control",
                "value": "control"
            },
            " of it.",
            " [incomplete]"
        ]
    },
    "control": {
        "title": "Control",
        "difficulty": 1,
        "description": [
            "A ",
            {
                "type": "glossary_button",
                "text": "positional",
                "value": "positional_chess"
            },
            " attribute describing the arrangement of a player's pieces or pawns to ",
            {
                "type": "glossary_button",
                "text": "cover",
                "value": "piece_vision"
            },
            " or otherwise block access to key squares, preventing the opponent from placing their own pieces or pawns on those",
            " squares and enabling the player to make use of them.",
            "\n\nTaking control of a square or region to deny it from the opponent is a form of ",
            {
                "type": "glossary_button",
                "text": "prophylaxis",
                "value": "prophylaxis",
                "punctuation": "."
            },
            "\n\nSquares or regions of the board can be controlled ",
            {
                "type": "wrap_italic",
                "text": "directly"
            },
            " (via coverage), or ",
            {
                "type": "wrap_italic",
                "text": "indirectly"
            },
            ":",
            {
                "type": "unordered_list",
                "items": [
                    [
                        "In the ",
                        {
                            "type": "set_moves_button",
                            "text": "King's Indian Defence",
                            "value": ["d4", "Nf6", "c4", "g6", "Nc3", "Bg7"],
                            "punctuation": ","
                        },
                        " Black ",
                        {
                            "type": "glossary_button",
                            "text": "fianchettos",
                            "value": "fianchetto"
                        },
                        " the kingside bishop. This exerts indirect control of the ",
                        {
                            "type": "glossary_button",
                            "text": "centre",
                            "value": "centre"
                        },
                        " - the bishop is",
                        " blocked by the knight, but x-rays e5 and the pawn on d4."
                    ],
                    [
                        "In ",
                        {
                            "type": "set_moves_button",
                            "text": "this position",
                            "value": "e4 Nf6 e5 Nd5 d4 d6 Nf3 Bg4 Be2 e6 O-O Be7 c4"
                        },
                        " from the main line of ",
                        {
                            "type": "wrap_italic",
                            "text": "Alekhine's Defence"
                        },
                        ", Black cannot move the ",
                        {
                            "type": "glossary_button",
                            "text": "hanging",
                            "value": "hanging"
                        },
                        " knight to b4 because White has indirect (or ",
                        {
                            "type": "glossary_button",
                            "text": "tactical",
                            "value": "tactics",
                            "punctuation": ")"
                        },
                        " control of it.",
                        "\n",
                        {
                            "type": "wrap_bold",
                            "text": "7. ...Nb4??"
                        },
                        " will be met with ",
                        {
                            "type": "wrap_bold",
                            "text": "8. Qa4+!"
                        },
                        ", ",
                        {
                            "type": "glossary_button",
                            "text": "forking",
                            "value": "forks"
                        },
                        " the knight and king, and if Black blocks the check with ",
                        {
                            "type": "wrap_bold",
                            "text": "N4c6"
                        },
                        " White can then pressure the ",
                        {
                            "type": "glossary_button",
                            "text": "pin",
                            "value": "pins"
                        },
                        " with ",
                        {
                            "type": "wrap_bold",
                            "text": "d5!"
                        },
                        " to win the knight."
                    ],
                    [
                        {
                            "type": "glossary_button",
                            "text": "Space",
                            "value": "space"
                        },
                        " is a form of indirect control."
                    ]
                ]
            }
        ]
    },
    "discovered_attacks": {
        "title": "Discovered Attacks",
        "difficulty": 1,
        "description": [
            "A ",
            {
                "type": "glossary_button",
                "text": "tactical",
                "value": "tactics"
            },
            " motif in which a direct attack by one piece is revealed when another piece or pawn is moved out of its way.",
            "\n\nIn ",
            {
                "type": "set_moves_button",
                "text": "this example",
                "value": ["e4", "e5", "Nf3", "Nf6", "Nxe5", "Nxe4", "Qe2", "Nf6", "Nc6+"]
            },
            " from ",
            {
                "type": "wrap_italic",
                "text": "Petrov's Defence"
            },
            ", Black makes the blunder ",
            {
                "type": "wrap_bold",
                "text": "4. ...Nf6??"
            },
            ", allowing White to play the crushing discovered check ",
            {
                "type": "wrap_bold",
                "text": "Nc6+!"
            },
            " in response.",
            "\nBy moving the knight out of the way, White's queen now ",
            {
                "type": "glossary_button",
                "text": "sees",
                "value": "piece_vision"
            },
            " Black's king, and White's knight is safe from immediate capture while Black spends their move blocking",
            " the check. White may then capture Black's queen with the knight on their next move.",
            "\nIn this case, the discovered attack is also a form of ",
            {
                "type": "glossary_button",
                "text": "double attack",
                "value": "double_attacks",
                "punctuation": ","
            },
            " as the knight and queen create two separate threats."
        ]
    },
    "backward_pawns": {
        "difficulty": 2,
        "title": "Backward Pawns",
        "description": [
            "A backward pawn is a pawn whose neighbouring pawns have advanced past it, meaning that it is the only pawn",
            " amongst its neighbours which cannot be defended by another pawn in its current location.",
            "\n\nBackward pawns are typically a ",
            {
                "type": "glossary_button",
                "text": "positional",
                "value": "positional_chess"
            },
            " weakness; if they cannot be easily advanced, they must be guarded by pieces instead of by other pawns, which",
            " necessitates tying those pieces down to their defence.",
            "\nIf a backward pawn is captured, its neighbouring pawns may also then become backward pawns as a consequence,",
            " resulting in the larger ",
            {
                "type": "glossary_button",
                "text": "pawn structure",
                "value": "pawn_structures"
            },
            " disintegrating as the weak spots multiply.",
            "\n\nBy its nature, a backward pawn also creates a ",
            {
                "type": "glossary_button",
                "text": "hole",
                "value": "holes"
            },
            " directly in front of it.",
            "\n\nIn ",
            {
                "type": "set_moves_button",
                "text": "this line",
                "value": "e4 c5 Nf3 d6 d4 cxd4 Nxd4 Nf6 Nc3 a6 Be2 e5"
            },
            " from the ",
            {
                "type": "wrap_italic",
                "text": "Najdorf Sicilian"
            },
            ", the e5 pawn push from Black creates a prominent backward pawn on d6. This ",
            {
                "type": "wrap_italic",
                "text": "can"
            },
            " pose a long-term weakness for Black, but comes with ",
            {
                "type": "glossary_button",
                "text": "compensation",
                "value": "imbalances"
            },
            " in the form of a foothold in the ",
            {
                "type": "glossary_button",
                "text": "centre",
                "value": "centre"
            },
            " which also ",
            {
                "type": "glossary_button",
                "text": "controls",
                "value": "control"
            },
            " the d4 square, with the potential to either use it as an ",
            {
                "type": "glossary_button",
                "text": "outpost",
                "value": "outposts"
            },
            " or to subsequently play the d5 ",
            {
                "type": "glossary_button",
                "text": "pawn break",
                "value": "pawn_breaks",
                "punctuation": "."
            }
        ]
    },
    "piece_vision": {
        "difficulty": 0,
        "title": "Piece Vision",
        "description": [
            "Piece vision, or ",
            {
                "type": "wrap_bold",
                "text": "coverage"
            },
            ", refers to the squares that a piece or pawn can capture another piece or pawn on from its current location.",
            "\n\nFor pieces which move along lines (bishops, rooks and queens), vision can apply pressure to a square even",
            " when there is another piece or pawn blocking the path - this is referred to as an ",
            {
                "type": "wrap_bold",
                "text": "x-ray"
            },
            ", and forms the basis for a variety of ",
            {
                "type": "glossary_button",
                "text": "tactics",
                "value": "tactics"
            },
            " such as ",
            {
                "type": "glossary_button",
                "text": "pins",
                "value": "pins",
                "punctuation": ","
            },
            " ",
            {
                "type": "glossary_button",
                "text": "skewers",
                "value": "skewers",
                "punctuation": ","
            },
            " and ",
            {
                "type": "glossary_button",
                "text": "discovered attacks",
                "value": "discovered_attacks",
                "punctuation": "."
            }
        ]
    },
    "prophylaxis": {
        "difficulty": 1,
        "title": "Prophylaxis",
        "description": [
            "In ",
            {
                "type": "glossary_button",
                "text": "positional",
                "value": "positional_chess"
            },
            " chess, a prophylactic move is a move made by a player to prevent their opponent from carrying out a plan that",
            " the player deems undesirable.",
            "\nThis can take a variety of forms, with some of the most common including ",
            {
                "type": "glossary_button",
                "text": "luft",
                "value": "luft"
            },
            " and ",
            {
                "type": "wrap_bold",
                "text": "area denial"
            },
            " (taking ",
            {
                "type": "glossary_button",
                "text": "control",
                "value": "control"
            },
            " of a square to prevent the opponent from making use of it)",
            "\n\nIn the ",
            {
                "type": "wrap_italic",
                "text": "Anti-Fried Liver Defence"
            },
            ", Black plays the prophylactic move ",
            {
                "type": "set_moves_button",
                "text": "3. ...h6",
                "value": ["e4", "e5", "Nf3", "Nc6", "Bc4", "h6"]
            },
            " to prevent White from placing their knight on g5 targeting the f7 square."
        ]
    }
}